FAFSA numbers are down

Current data from Form Your Future's FAFSA Tracker shows that nearly half of Nebraska's seniors have not yet completed a FAFSA. Please advise your seniors that it's not too late to complete the form, especially since some colleges have extended their FAFSA priority dates.

In addition, students must submit a FAFSA by June 1 to be considered for the Nebraska Promise program. This University of Nebraska program, which replaces CollegeBound, covers tuition for students who meet academic qualifications and have a family income of $60,000 or less (Adjusted Gross Income/AGI) or are Pell Grant-eligible.

EducationQuest staff is available to help your students complete the FAFSA via a free virtual appointment. They can contact us to make an appointment or ask questions using our new live chat at EducationQuest.org.

Recently, the faculty of Concordia University, Nebraska approved a proposal for test-optional admission to begin immediately for fall 2020 applicants and beyond.

This proposal specifically states that any high school senior applying to Concordia with a 3.0 or higher cumulative GPA will be admitted without submission of standardized test scores (ACT or SAT). Those applying with a GPA lower than 3.0 will be required to submit standardized test scores as part of their admissions process. Academic scholarships for all accepted high school seniors, currently ranging from $13,000-$21,000 per year, will now be based solely on the student’s GPA as opposed to GPA + standardized test scores. Concordia will still encourage all admitted students to submit standardized test scores prior to enrolling for the purposes of class placement and consideration for our Luke Scholar Honors Program.

Online Manufacturing Training

As your organization rethinks, redesigns and reallocates resources during this challenging time, we wanted to make you aware of a resource to help support your training needs.

Our partner, Tooling U-SME, works with organizations across the country educating employees in a multitude of manufacturing programs such as Machining, Industrial Maintenance/Mechatronics, Welding, Additive Manufacturing, Robotics, and more.

Tooling U-SME courses are online, making this a great option for your employees that are being asked to work remotely or are taking time off to be home due to family needs. With a user-friendly app for tablets and phones classes can be taken anywhere!

Please reach out to Marguerite Himmelberg at mhimmelberg@southeast.edu to learn more about special training options we have available and how we can help you during this challenging time.

Register for Careers in Transportation Day!

The transportation industry has a variety of in demand, high impact, and
technology driven careers. SCC's Careers in Transportation Day will give students
hands-on opportunities to explore several transportation related career fields.

Participants will learn from industry leaders and SCC instructors and will
work alongside current SCC students. This is also the perfect opportunity
to see SCC's new Crete Carrier Diesel Technology and Welding Center!

Participants will select career interest areas and have
the opportunity to participate in hands-on stations.

2020 Event Details:
Wednesday, February 19, 2020
Event Check-In: 8:30 a.m. - 9:00 a.m.
Event: 9:00 a.m. - 2:00 p.m.
Welsh Center, Milford Campus

Register now.

post_text: The Saunders County Prevention Coalition in partnership with Wahoo High School, is holding a Digital Citizenship Presentation on Wednesday, November 29th at 6pm at the Wahoo High School Learning Lab. The Learning Lab is right off of the lunch room in the High School. This will be a 1 hour presentation that will detail to parents and community members the importance of safe and legal use of digital technology. It will focus on how to be a responsible digital citizen. It will hit on hot topics such as sending inappropriate pictures of minors (even if the person sending the photo is a minor), digital bullying, digital footprints and much more. It will cover each person’s legal responsibility as well.
